  "body": "### What is wrong?\r\n\r\n`PeerPool` provides an API to add subscribers (which get notified about new peers), and those subscribers then use `Peer.read_sub_proto_msg()` to read the messages sent by the remote. That works fine when we have a single subscriber but since all subscribers get a reference to the same `Peer` instance and that instance uses a single `asyncio.Queue` in `read_sub_proto_msg()`, it cannot handle multiple subscribers.\r\n\r\nRight now this is not really a problem as our `PeerPool` instances never seem to have more than one subscriber at the same time.\r\n\r\n### How can it be fixed\r\n\r\n`Peer` must use a separate `asyncio.Queue` to store the sub-proto msgs for every subscriber. That may also require us to drop the `read_sub_proto_msg()` method and add a new API to subscribe, which would then return the subscriber's queue",
